<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1867-06-05T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1867-06-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="289" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d289">
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <head><persName type="from">M . F. W. Seward</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr. Campbell</persName></head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 34.]</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State,</hi>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington,</hi>
                                </placeName>
                                <date calendar="gregorian" when="1867-06-05"><hi rend="italic">June</hi> 5, 1867</date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>On inquiry it is found that both the vessels you mention are employed in
                            other duty, from which they cannot be spared; and the Navy Department
                            has none in your vicinity that is available. You will therefore proceed
                            by whatever conveyance or route you may find most speedy or
                            practicable.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>F. W. SEWARD, <hi rend="italic">Acting Secretary.</hi></signed>
                        </closer>
                        <postscript>
                            <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Lewis D. Campbell,</hi> Esq., <hi rend="italic">New Orleans.</hi></p>
                        </postscript>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>